27. Albano in monte: ‘quia Egeria nympha dicebatur loqui cum Numa Pompilio in Albano monte' Acron. This legend does not appear elsewhere in quite the same form3 but Ritter labours hard to show that it is equivalent to that which places the grove of Egeria at Aricia, which was not indeed on, but at the foot of the Alban mount. Cp: Ov. Met. XV. 487, Servius on Verg. Aen. V11. 763 eductum Egeriae lucis. Ov. Fast. 111. 261—2. He is however clearly wrong in supposing this grove at Aricia to be that mentioned in Juv. 111. 17, which was close to the Capene gate at Rome, sixteen miles away. Burn
